with glassware and cutlery?

00:36:22.620 --> 00:36:27.280
&gt;&gt; No. We kind of hoped at
one point that maybe one

00:36:27.280 --> 00:36:32.490 position:56%
of those china services would turn
into a new set of glassware instead.

00:36:32.490 --> 00:36:37.100
What we're finding is like
everyone can probably attest to,

00:36:37.100 --> 00:36:39.820
the luxury trades in
America have gone

00:36:39.820 --> 00:36:42.900
down the tubes to a large extent.

00:36:42.900 --> 00:36:48.600
Finding American glass
is almostt impossible.

00:36:48.600 --> 00:36:56.770
The glassware that Mrs. Kennedy
first ordered in 1961 sorry.

00:36:56.770 --> 00:37:00.870
The glassware that she bought you
know was just absolutely plane.

00:37:00.870 --> 00:37:04.010
The previous glassware that
had been bought in the 1930's

00:37:04.010 --> 00:37:05.870
for Franklin Roosevelt was cut.

00:37:05.870 --> 00:37:08.020
And she said I really think
we should have glassware

00:37:08.020 --> 00:37:11.430
if you break it no one gets mad

00:37:11.430 --> 00:37:15.000
because cut glass is
expensive and hard to replace.

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.350
So it was made by a
company in West Virginia.

00:37:17.350 --> 00:37:19.650
Then it was -- that company
was bought out and it was made

00:37:19.650 --> 00:37:21.060
by another company in West Virginia

00:37:21.060 --> 00:37:23.190
and then it was made
by a Company in Ohio.

00:37:23.190 --> 00:37:25.520
And it was made by Lenox
and then Lenox closed

00:37:25.520 --> 00:37:31.040
up its glass factories
and so, so it's hard.

00:37:31.040 --> 00:37:34.520
The flatware we have two
principle services of flatware.

00:37:34.520 --> 00:37:40.050 position:56%
Gilded silver which is actually an
amalgamation of its storage silvers.

00:37:40.050 --> 00:37:42.700
So there are forks from the 1890's,

00:37:42.700 --> 00:37:46.180
knives from the 1920's,
spoons from the 1950's.

00:37:46.180 --> 00:37:50.940
All kind of based on silver
from the Andrew Jackson era

00:37:50.940 --> 00:37:53.520
that are often used
for state dinners.

00:37:53.520 --> 00:37:56.380
And then there's a silver
service that was provided

00:37:56.380 --> 00:37:59.900
in the Ford administration
that we bought from Gorham.

00:37:59.900 --> 00:38:03.760
It was a pattern that was called
-- it's called King Charles.

00:38:03.760 --> 00:38:05.420
It's actually the King
George pattern

00:38:05.420 --> 00:38:07.000
or the Traditional King's pattern.

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:08.950
They renamed it King Charles

00:38:08.950 --> 00:38:11.830
because they were selling
it in historic Charleston.

00:38:11.830 --> 00:38:16.570
And so, so it's used -- it does
not have Whitehouse written on it.

00:38:16.570 --> 00:38:19.940
All the other earlier silvers
including the gilded service is

00:38:19.940 --> 00:38:23.420
engraved Presidents House
which is the traditional words

00:38:23.420 --> 00:38:25.000
on the silver services.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:30.470
The old early 19th century name
for it rather than Whitehouse.

00:38:30.470 --> 00:38:33.960
So they, they seem to
serve our purposes well.

00:38:33.960 --> 00:38:37.880
You know there could be a time what
the first lady would say I wish we

00:38:37.880 --> 00:38:41.970
had something that looked more
modern then these very 18th century

00:38:41.970 --> 00:38:46.170
flatware services and the same
could be said for the glass.

00:38:46.170 --> 00:38:48.970
I know our -- the head of our
food service people didn't'

00:38:48.970 --> 00:38:50.270
like Mrs. Kennedy's glass.

00:38:50.270 --> 00:38:53.930
By the time we were into the 21st
century said these are glasses

00:38:53.930 --> 00:38:57.430
that are too small for
modern drinking and,

00:38:57.430 --> 00:39:01.740
and you know champagne should be a
flute and not a tulip and you know.

00:39:01.740 --> 00:39:05.990
So he would be all for
a new glass service.

