either choose a service

00:39:16.570 --> 00:39:19.360
from a different administration
for a dinner party

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:23.140
or more permanent furniture
such as President Obama's choice

00:39:23.140 --> 00:39:27.220
to use the resolute
desk in his oval office.

00:39:27.220 --> 00:39:33.790
&gt;&gt; Well the resolute desk is
a wonderful piece of furniture

00:39:33.790 --> 00:39:36.690
that was commissioned by
Queen Victoria to give

00:39:36.690 --> 00:39:40.640
to President Rutherford
Hayes in 1880.

00:39:40.640 --> 00:39:44.440
It's a great big partner's
kind of desk.

00:39:44.440 --> 00:39:49.630
Franklin Roosevelt commissioned a
presidential seal to inset so that

00:39:49.630 --> 00:39:52.320
if he were sitting on the other
side you couldn't see his,

00:39:52.320 --> 00:39:53.990
his leg braces.

00:39:53.990 --> 00:39:57.750
It was used in the private quarters

00:39:57.750 --> 00:40:00.100
until President Kennedy
put it in the oval office.

00:40:00.100 --> 00:40:03.780
And that made a big, that was a
big symbolic statement bringing

00:40:03.780 --> 00:40:06.610
out historic object
and Mrs. Kennedy's work

00:40:06.610 --> 00:40:09.870
to be more museum like.

00:40:09.870 --> 00:40:13.960
It then traveled as a result of
President Kennedy's assassination.

00:40:13.960 --> 00:40:18.650
It was like part of his package
and so it didn't come back

00:40:18.650 --> 00:40:23.040
to the Whitehouse until President
Carter asked for it back in 1977.

00:40:23.040 --> 00:40:26.320
So it's been used by every
president in the oval office except

00:40:26.320 --> 00:40:30.700 position:56%
for George H. W. Busch who preferred
to use his vice presidential desk

00:40:30.700 --> 00:40:34.940
since he had a desk in the West
Wing for continuity, but he used it

00:40:34.940 --> 00:40:36.970
in the private residence.

00:40:36.970 --> 00:40:40.820
Other things that are symbolic
obviously in this new china

00:40:40.820 --> 00:40:46.190 position:56%
that the presidential seal has made
an appearance on three of the pieces

00:40:46.190 --> 00:40:48.490
out of the 11 that are
part of the Obama china.

00:40:48.490 --> 00:40:51.640
The traditional places to put
it are on the service plate.

00:40:51.640 --> 00:40:53.120
The first thing you
see at the table.

00:40:53.120 --> 00:40:55.880
And the dessert plate the last
thing you see at the table.

00:40:55.880 --> 00:40:57.380
And the service plate is

00:40:57.380 --> 00:41:01.270
in the center you know no
foods actually served on it.

00:41:01.270 --> 00:41:03.260
In this case it's also on
the side of the little cup

00:41:03.260 --> 00:41:06.460
and saucer that's part
of the last course.

00:41:06.460 --> 00:41:10.100
Other services had more eagles.

00:41:10.100 --> 00:41:12.970
Mrs. Johnson actually in,
in designing the china that,

00:41:12.970 --> 00:41:17.960 position:56%
that Connie mentioned working on for
the flowers for the dessert plates.

00:41:17.960 --> 00:41:21.370
She took the eagle off
the 1817 Monroe china.

00:41:21.370 --> 00:41:23.970
She really went back to
a historical president.

00:41:23.970 --> 00:41:30.860 position:56%
Put a very early American version of
the eagle and then put wild flowers

00:41:30.860 --> 00:41:34.390
around the, the, the, the
borders of some of the plates

00:41:34.390 --> 00:41:36.980
to represent her interest
in the roadside

00:41:36.980 --> 00:41:39.400
and the preservation of the land.

00:41:39.400 --> 00:41:43.770 position:56%
And then the 51 different dessert
plates had the state flower for each

00:41:43.770 --> 00:41:46.800
of the 50 states and the
District of Columbia so.

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:50.310
So sometimes symbolism
built into the china.

00:41:50.310 --> 00:41:53.790
I know with the, the Obama
china there's a certain amount

00:41:53.790 --> 00:41:55.820
of streamlining in the design.

00:41:55.820 --> 00:41:58.440
And that was designed to
represent there interest

00:41:58.440 --> 00:42:02.470 position:56%
in the abstract and the more modern.

00:42:02.470 --> 00:42:06.770
Mrs. Busch, Laura Busch picked
a very nontraditional eagle

00:42:06.770 --> 00:42:08.070
for her state china.

00:42:08.070 --> 00:42:12.750 position:56%
It was an inlay in the sideboard in
the family dining room that had a --

00:42:12.750 --> 00:42:15.220
sideboard that had
belonged to Daniel Webster

00:42:15.220 --> 00:42:18.870
and she just thought you know
it was very much more naive

00:42:18.870 --> 00:42:22.370
than a traditional you know defined

00:42:22.370 --> 00:42:24.870
by a Harold Dreversen
[phonetic] kind of eagle.

00:42:24.870 --> 00:42:29.790
But that's what she wanted so
that's what went on her china so.

00:42:29.790 --> 00:42:32.860
And really our office is not
the arbiter of the design.

00:42:32.860 --> 00:42:34.400
You know we suggest.

